("The task is to programmatically scan and clean LaTeX preamble text by removing all references to the hyperref package. This includes different forms: \\usepackage{hyperref}, \\hypersetup{...}, and hyperref-provided macros like \\urlstyle.\n\nLet me consider the most reliable approaches:\n\n1. Regular expressions might work for simple cases but could be error-prone for complex LaTeX with nested structures, comments, etc.\n\n2. A proper LaTeX parser would be most reliable but might be overkill and complex to implement.\n\n3. A hybrid approach with careful regex patterns might be a good middle ground.\n\nFor a reliable solution, I should consider:\n- Handling package loading with options: \\usepackage[options]{hyperref}\n- Handling package loading in lists: \\usepackage{graphicx,hyperref,amsmath}\n- Handling multi-line \\hypersetup commands with nested braces\n- Identifying hyperref-specific commands\n- Preserving other content"
 "For reliable LaTeX preamble cleaning, I'd recommend a multi-stage approach using regular expressions with careful pattern matching:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\ndef remove_hyperref(preamble):\n    # Remove \\usepackage{hyperref} and variants with options\n    preamble = re.sub(r'\\\\usepackage(?:\\s*\\[[^\\]]*\\])?\\s*\\{(?:[^{}]*,)?hyperref(?:,[^{}]*)?\\}', \n                      lambda m: re.sub(r'(?:,)?hyperref(?:,)?', ',', m.group(0)).replace(',,', ',').replace('{,}', '{}').replace('{}', '', 1), \n                      preamble)\n    \n    # Remove entire \\hypersetup blocks\n    preamble = re.sub(r'\\\\hypersetup\\s*\\{[^{}]*(?:\\{[^{}]*\\}[^{}]*)*\\}', '', preamble)\n    \n    # Remove specific hyperref commands\n    hyperref_commands = [r'\\\\urlstyle\\s*\\{[^{}]*\\}', \n                        r'\\\\hyperbaseurl\\s*\\{[^{}]*\\}',\n                        r'\\\\href\\s*\\{[^{}]*\\}\\s*\\{[^{}]*\\}']\n    \n    for cmd in hyperref_commands:\n        preamble = re.sub(cmd, '', preamble)\n    \n    # Clean up empty lines and multiple spaces\n    preamble = re.sub(r'\\n\\s*\\n+', '\\n\\n', preamble)\n    \n    return preamble\n```\n\nFor complex documents, consider using a dedicated LaTeX parser like `plasTeX` or `TexSoup` which can handle the document structure more reliably than regex alone.\n\nThe most challenging case is balanced braces in `\\hypersetup` - regex can't properly handle arbitrary nesting depth, so for extremely complex preambles, you might need to implement a simple parser that counts opening/closing braces.")
